He goes on to compare the incident with the story of the Rape of Europa, the relevancy of the tale being that, in each case, the chief actor was supposed to have been a god disguised in the form of a bull. He also compares the received origin of the fount of Hippocrene on Mount Helicon, which was reputed to have been due to a kick from the hoof of Pegasus, and claims that Greece be not allowed a monopoly of such wonders.

There was doubtless here, as may be gathered from lines 269 sq., a temple dedicated to the Nymphs, such as Pliny tells us was to be found at the fountain of Clitumnus, on the road between Fuligno and Spoleto.
